{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15979"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15979"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8670"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65957"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8597"},{"type":"tags","id":"8598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the inner cell mass undergoes differentiation to form a bilaminar embryonic disc. This process involves the formation of two distinct cell layers with different developmental fates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of the primary yolk sac?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops from proliferating epiblast cells","Forms directly from trophoblast cells","Derives from proliferating hypoblast cells","Originates from extraembryonic mesoderm","Develops from cytotrophoblast invasion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ederives from proliferating hypoblast cells\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes primary yolk sac formation. After implantation, the inner cell mass differentiates into two layers: the hypoblast (lower layer) and epiblast (upper layer). The hypoblast cells proliferate and migrate to form the primary yolk sac.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops from proliferating epiblast cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The epiblast forms the amnion, not the primary yolk sac\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms directly from trophoblast cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Trophoblasts contribute to placental development, not yolk sac formation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOriginates from extraembryonic mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E - Extraembryonic mesoderm develops later and is not involved in primary yolk sac formation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops from cytotrophoblast invasion\u003C/strong\u003E - Cytotrophoblasts are involved in implantation but not yolk sac development\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe primary yolk sac is a temporary structure that is later replaced by the secondary yolk sac during further development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The primary yolk sac forms from proliferating hypoblast cells during the second week after implantation.","The inner cell mass differentiates into two layers: hypoblast (forms primary yolk sac) and epiblast (forms amnion).","The bilaminar embryonic disc stage is a crucial step in early human development occurring after implantation."],"references":["Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Donovan MF, Arbor TC, Bordoni B. Embryology, Yolk Sac. [Updated 2023 Mar 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555965/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65957"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15979"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65957"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T08:10:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T08:13:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8670"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":